text:
The Underestimation of Donald J. Trump: A Story of Political Mastery

The 2024 presidential election was nothing short of a political spectacle, where Donald J. Trump, once again, proved his detractors wrong. The narrative often pushed by the liberal elite, the media, and Hollywood portrayed Trump as a buffoon, a relic of outdated politics, and an easy target for defeat. However, this underestimation became Trump's secret weapon.

The Liberal Elite's Misjudgment:

From the outset, many in the liberal elite viewed Trump as an anachronism, a candidate who could energize the base but never capture the middle ground. His outsider status, his brash style, and his unfiltered rhetoric were seen as liabilities. Yet, they failed to recognize that these very traits resonated with a segment of Americans feeling alienated by what they perceived as an out-of-touch establishment.

Media's Role:

The media, often accused of liberal bias, played into Trump's hands with every negative headline. Each piece critiquing his character, his policies, or his past business dealings inadvertently kept him in the public eye. Trump understood media dynamics better than most; he turned every attack into an opportunity, using media coverage as free advertising. His ability to dominate the news cycle with controversial statements meant that even those who opposed him couldn't stop talking about him.

Hollywood's Disconnect:

Hollywood, a bastion of liberal thought, ridiculed Trump, with celebrities openly declaring their intent to leave if he won. This disconnect with a large swath of America allowed Trump to position himself as the anti-elite candidate. He appealed directly to those who felt Hollywood was out of touch with the real concerns of everyday Americans, like jobs, security, and national identity.

Connecting with the American People:

- Direct Communication: Trump bypassed traditional media gatekeepers by speaking directly to the people via rallies, social media, and his own platform. His rallies were not just campaign events; they were communal gatherings where supporters felt heard and seen.

- Tapping into Discontent: He articulated the frustrations of those who felt left behind by globalization and technological change, blaming these on policies favored by the liberal elite.

- The Outsider Image: His outsider status was not just a campaign slogan; it was a badge of honor for those tired of career politicians. Trump's narrative as a successful businessman fighting against the political establishment struck a chord.

- Resilience in the Face of Adversity: Every obstacle from lawsuits to attempts on his life only reinforced his image as a fighter. This resilience was not just admired; it was revered by his supporters.

The underestimation by those who thought they wielded cultural and political power over America was Trump's greatest advantage. He turned their scorn into a rallying cry for his supporters. The presidency was not just won; it was seized by an understanding that in American politics, being underestimated can be a formidable weapon if wielded with the right strategy and tenacity.

In the end, Donald Trump's victory in 2024 was a reminder of a fundamental political truth: sometimes, it's not about how much you are loved by the elite, but how deeply you connect with the electorate's heart.

author/description: Chief White House Correspondent and Founder of "The Daily Letter" ‚û°Ô∏è https://t.co/JXBChWSOCp
text:
NOTE: The Department of Justice has filed a motion to dismiss the criminal case against President-elect Donald J. Trump, who is set to be inaugurated on January 20, 2025. The motion cites longstanding DOJ policy and constitutional interpretations by the Office of Legal Counsel (OLC), which prohibit the indictment and prosecution of a sitting President.

Everything about this case as I repeated said was and still is unprecedented, as Trump was indicted and prosecuted as a private citizen, but his election to the presidency has triggered the application of the OLC's prohibition. The Special Counsel, bound by this interpretation, argues that the case must be dismissed before Trump's inauguration, regardless of the allegations or stage of the proceedings.

The government writes, "As a result of the election held on November 5, 2024, the defendant, Donald J. Trump, will be inaugurated as President on January 20, 2025. It has long been the position of the Department of Justice that the United States Constitution forbids the federal indictment and subsequent criminal prosecution of a sitting President. But the Department and the country have never faced the circumstance here, where a federal indictment against a private citizen has been returned by a grand jury and a criminal prosecution is already underway when the defendant is elected President.

"Confronted with this unprecedented situation, the Special Counsel‚Äôs Office consulted with the Department‚Äôs Office of Legal Counsel (OLC), whose interpretation of constitutional questions such as those raised here is binding on Department prosecutors. After careful consideration, the Department has determined that OLC‚Äôs prior opinions concerning the Constitution‚Äôs prohibition on federal indictment and prosecution of a sitting President apply to this situation and that as a result, this prosecution must be dismissed before the defendant is inaugurated.

"That prohibition is binding on the Department‚Äôs Special Counsel and applies regardless of the seriousness of the allegations or the procedural posture of the case. Accordingly, the Government respectfully moves for the dismissal of this case."

text:
Rural counties in California, Illinois push to secede from blue states to separate from liberal-run cities after Trump‚Äôs win: ‚ÄòSo flipping excited‚Äô | Ryan King, New York Post

They‚Äôve had enough.

A movement in a myriad of rural counties across deep blue states such as Illinois and California to split off and form new states appears to be gaining some steam in the wake of the Nov. 5 election.

Conservative residents of the rural regions are taking note of their peers fleeing to lower-taxed and less-regulated red states but they are ready to stay put ‚Äî pining for a divorce with the urban sectors of their state.

A group dubbed the New Illinois State has drafted a new constitution and championed plans to ‚ÄúLeave Illinois Without Moving.‚Äù¬†On Election Day, seven rural counties in Illinois voted to contemplate splitting off from the state.

‚ÄúThere‚Äôs a lot of people in Chicago, and I think that they make a lot of decisions that affect people downstate,‚Äù Phil Gioja, from Iroquois County, told the Wall Street Journal.

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs just sending a message that, ‚ÄòHey, you know, there‚Äôs people that would like to be part of the conversation, and often aren‚Äôt.‚Äô‚Äù

In Iroquois County, about 73% of voters backed the idea of banding together with other counties in Illinois, except Cook County, which encompasses Chicago and forming a new state. Chicago is home to about 40% of Illinois‚Äô population.

While Gioja doesn‚Äôt anticipate a separation soon, some backers of a rural divorce think that an opening will come.

‚ÄúWe always believed that our best opportunity to negotiate our way out of Illinois was when Illinois was approaching that financial cliff ‚Äî it‚Äôs been on a path toward it for years,‚Äù G.H. Merritt, who chairs New Illinois State told the outlet.

Out in California, a similar movement has taken root as well. The New California State organization hopes to splinter off the counties outside the Bay Area, Sacramento and Los Angeles.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm so flipping excited,‚Äù Paul Preston, who founded New California State, told the Wall Street Journal.
